Let F be a formula in the language of ZF with (at most) x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n},y free. We say that F is an n-ary definable mapping if the following conditions hold:
\forall a_{1},\ldots ,a_{n}.\mkern 5mu\exists b.\mkern 5muF{\mathopen {}[a_{i}/x_{i},b/y]\mathclose {}};
\forall a_{1},\ldots ,a_{n},b,b'.\mkern 5muF{\mathopen {}[a_{i}/x_{i},b/y]\mathclose {}} \wedge F{\mathopen {}[a_{i}/x_{i},b'/y]\mathclose {}} \Rightarrow b = b'. We write F(a_{1},\ldots ,a_{n}) for the unique b such that F{\mathopen {}[a_{i}/x_{i},b/y]\mathclose {}} holds.

A relation R\colon A\nrightarrow A is an equivalence relation if the following properties hold:

reflexive: \forall a \in  A.\mkern 5mu(a,a) \in  R;

symmetric: \forall a,a' \in  A.\mkern 5mu(a,a') \in  R \Rightarrow  (a',a) \in  R;

transitive: \forall a,b,c \in  A.\mkern 5mu(a,b) \in  R \wedge  (b,c) \in  R \Rightarrow  (a,c) \in  R.

A set N is called a natural number set if it is equipped with

an element 0 \in  N;

a successor function s\colon N\to N.
  These data are subject to the following requirements.

s\colon N\to N is injective;

non-looping: for every x \in  N, s(x) \neq  0;

induction principle: for every set P \subseteq  N, if 0 \in  P and for all x \in  N, x \in  P implies that s(x) \in  P then P = N.

Let x_{0} be given and F be a definable mapping. Then there is a unique function f with \mathsf {dom}(f) = \mathbb {N} such that
f(0) = x_{0};
f(s(n)) = F(f(n)).

We approximate the required function f by means of n-germs. An n-germ is a function f_{n} with \mathsf {dom}(f_{n}) = s(n) such that
f_{n}(0) = x_{0};
f_{n}(s(m)) = F(f_{n}(m)) for all m < n. By induction, we show that each n-germ exists uniquely.

An ordinal is a set \alpha  such that

(\alpha ,\in ) is a (strict) well order;

\alpha  is transitive.
